WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:06.710
Hi.

00:00:06.710 --> 00:00:09.200
I'm Diane Solinger, and I
am the manager of the

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:10.800
GooglersGive team.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:14.340
GooglersGive is the team that
helps you give and volunteer

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:15.470
as Googlers.

00:00:15.470 --> 00:00:19.190
And last fall we started-- or
actually, last November-- we

00:00:19.190 --> 00:00:22.340
started thinking about how we
can bring Googlers together

00:00:22.340 --> 00:00:25.430
around causes in thematic areas
of social interest.

00:00:25.430 --> 00:00:28.700
And we launched the first hunger
campaign, hunger and

00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:31.530
poverty alleviation, in
November of last year.

00:00:31.530 --> 00:00:35.920
It brought together about 6,000
Googlers via a quiz

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:38.250
about learning about the issues
around hunger and then

00:00:38.250 --> 00:00:39.270
giving and volunteering

00:00:39.270 --> 00:00:41.260
opportunities around the world.

00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:44.500
So we decided let's look at
Earth Day and the environment.

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:47.930
We know Googlers are very, very
concerned about the state

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:50.280
of our planet and are trying
to find ways to make a

00:00:50.280 --> 00:00:51.350
difference.

00:00:51.350 --> 00:00:55.050
And in particular, what we've
seen is a strong interest in

00:00:55.050 --> 00:00:58.270
wildlife, wildlife preservation,
conservation.

00:00:58.270 --> 00:01:01.470
And so the theme for the
environment campaign really

00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:03.120
took that turn and that twist.

00:01:03.120 --> 00:01:05.459
The environment campaign
actually ends today.

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:07.660
And so this is the capstone
event of the environment

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:09.280
campaign that launched
on Earth Day.

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:12.320
The next big thing coming up is
GoogleServe, which will be

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:13.710
June 7 through 14.

00:01:13.710 --> 00:01:16.040
And I saw philanthropy
on the [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:17.660
And I don't know if our

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:18.860
wonderful ambassador [? Erin ?]

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:20.560
had something to do with
that or somebody

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:21.720
else here at YouTube.

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:25.020
But there's a great story of
some of the things that people

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:26.510
did in GoogleServe last year.

00:01:26.510 --> 00:01:29.000
And we hope that you participate
in volunteering

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.930
for a GoogleServe project coming
up June 7 through 14.

00:01:32.930 --> 00:01:35.320
Today, we're here to
really focus on

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:36.370
the environment campaign.

00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:39.940
We're really lucky to have an
eminent expert in wildlife

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:43.220
conservation and preservation in
Peter Knights from WildAid.

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:47.470
We're going to start with
a short video to

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:48.920
kind of set the context.

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:51.810
The way it's going to go today
is we're going to have a

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:55.210
little visual and then have a
little talk and then a little

00:01:55.210 --> 00:01:57.380
visual and a little talk.

00:01:57.380 --> 00:01:59.230
And then we'll end it
with questions and

00:01:59.230 --> 00:02:00.160
answers from you.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:03.830
So with that, let's roll the
first video from WildAid to

00:02:03.830 --> 00:02:04.720
set the stage.

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:19.400
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:21.890
-You don't have to be the
world's fastest man to beat a

00:02:21.890 --> 00:02:23.140
speeding bullet.

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:28.990
Support conservation, and we
can save our big cats.

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:31.368
When we all come together--

00:02:31.368 --> 00:02:33.236
-We can do anything.

00:02:33.236 --> 00:02:33.710
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:35.950
DIANE SOLINGER: WildAid is a
perfect fit for YouTube.

00:02:35.950 --> 00:02:37.990
This is what they do to get the
message across about what

00:02:37.990 --> 00:02:40.900
we can do to save endangered
species around the world.

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:43.610
And as I said, we're really,
really lucky to have Peter

00:02:43.610 --> 00:02:46.090
Knights here, the executive
director of WildAid.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:47.880
Peter and I were talking a
little bit over lunch.

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:49.230
What a background you have.

00:02:49.230 --> 00:02:51.990
Let's explain to the group why
you are the executive director

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:54.200
of WildAid and what
WildAid does.

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:55.400
PETER KNIGHTS: Last man
standing, basically.

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:59.375
But I started off my career
originally I was an economist.

00:02:59.375 --> 00:03:01.040
I went to London School
of Economics.

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:04.050
And I left university, and I
didn't know what I wanted to

00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:05.140
do when I grew up.

00:03:05.140 --> 00:03:08.560
And I knew that I didn't want
to dedicate my life just to

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:09.350
making money.

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:11.580
Big mistake but--

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:12.230
with hindsight.

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:15.930
But really, my ambition has
always been to try and leave

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:18.430
the world a tiny bit
better off when I

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:19.760
leave than when I joined.

00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:24.530
And I believe the environment is
one of the areas where, no

00:03:24.530 --> 00:03:26.800
matter who you are or where you
are or how much money you

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:28.320
have, we all share the
same environment.

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:29.880
We all stand to lose
elephants.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:31.440
We all have to breathe
the same air.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:34.160
And I think if ever we're going
to learn how to work

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:36.720
together, as opposed to fight
each other and compete, it's

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:37.900
going to be through
the environment.

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:39.740
So that's why I decided
to do this.

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:43.930
And the first thing that I got
involved with was Greenpeace.

00:03:43.930 --> 00:03:46.830
And through that, I met some
people from an organization

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:49.190
called the Environmental
Investigation Agency.

00:03:49.190 --> 00:03:52.880
And they specialized in doing
undercover investigations of

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:54.350
illegal wildlife trade.

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:57.610
So we would create
fake companies,

00:03:57.610 --> 00:03:58.830
fake business cards.

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:02.820
It was faxes in those days, not
internet, to date myself.

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:05.000
And we would try and infiltrate
the illegal

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:06.750
wildlife trade to find
out what was going.

00:04:06.750 --> 00:04:11.270
And then using extremely badly
hidden cameras, we would film

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:13.910
people and put that on
television to try and move

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:16.630
governments forward to
try and stop some of

00:04:16.630 --> 00:04:18.930
these abuses of wildlife.

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:23.080
And then from that, I got to
work in 40-odd countries

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:25.790
worldwide on different illegal
wildlife problems.

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:28.000
And a lot of the work
led to Asia.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.180
And in Asia what we found was
that people just didn't

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:31.130
understand the problem.

00:04:31.130 --> 00:04:34.480
So it wasn't that people were
maliciously didn't care about

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:37.130
rhinos or elephants or
bears or sharks.

00:04:37.130 --> 00:04:38.680
They just didn't associate
these products

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:40.060
with the actual animals.

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:41.910
Nor were they aware that these
animals were becoming

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:45.800
endangered, driven by the trade
in their body parts.

00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:49.200
So it became clear that what
was needed was a massive

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:51.770
education and awareness
campaign.

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:55.000
And hence we started
to work with media.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.730
And environment is often
very bad news.

00:04:58.730 --> 00:05:00.660
And people can only take
so much bad news.

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:03.780
So what we try and do through
our campaigns is to keep these

00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:08.170
issues interesting, exciting,
not hopeless.

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:10.290
Because I don't believe any of
these things are hopeless.

00:05:10.290 --> 00:05:12.720
And very often, environmental,
you go, my god, I want to

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:14.230
shoot myself after I
heard that story.

00:05:14.230 --> 00:05:16.250
But in actual fact,
there is hope, and

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:17.280
there is a way forward.

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:20.590
And that's been the spirit of
the campaigns, using not only

00:05:20.590 --> 00:05:23.270
athletes but also
celebrities--

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:25.650
Jackie Chan has been with us
for a number of years doing

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:28.270
projects, and people
like Yao Ming and

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:29.720
influential business leaders--

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:31.160
to get the message over.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:34.660
So asking people from China to
talk to Chinese rather than us

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:37.020
as Americans talking
to the Chinese.

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:39.390
DIANE SOLINGER: And so WildAid
has certain focus areas for

00:05:39.390 --> 00:05:40.280
your programs.

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:43.780
And explain what those are
and why you chose those.

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:46.670
PETER KNIGHTS: Well, we take a
couple of different questions,

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:48.570
and we ask what do we do
and what don't we do.

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:50.630
The first thing, is somebody
else doing it?

00:05:50.630 --> 00:05:52.910
In which case we're like, fine,
we don't need to do it.

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:54.640
But secondly is also
can we make an

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:55.900
impact on those issues?

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:59.900
And so, most recently, we've
spent a lot of time working on

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:03.090
the shark fin soup issue and
sharks, and what are, to me,

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:05.500
one of the biggest environmental
disasters going

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:09.640
on, up to 73 million sharks
killed a year

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:11.100
for shark fin soup.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:13.510
And this is an industry which
used to be very small, and it

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:14.380
was very high end.

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:16.100
So it used to be very limited.

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:19.000
And with the economic growth in
China, in particular, we've

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.840
just seen this business
explode.

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:23.170
And sharks are very slow
reproducing animals.

00:06:23.170 --> 00:06:25.350
They're not designed really to
be preyed on by other animals.

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:27.350
They're usually top
of the food chain.

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:29.880
And human beings have come
in as a super predator.

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:31.540
And it's been pretty
disastrous to shark

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:32.240
populations.

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:35.380
And even to the extent in
Chinese, the shark fin soup is

00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:37.380
called fish wing soup.

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:39.440
People don't even know it's
coming from sharks, let alone

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:41.460
the biology of sharks which
makes them so vulnerable.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:43.720
So that's been a major campaign
we've been working

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:46.690
on, recently with some pretty
significant success in that.

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:48.000
DIANE SOLINGER: Shall
we show the--

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:48.380
PETER KNIGHTS: Sure.

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:49.630
DIANE SOLINGER: --shark
fin video?

00:06:49.630 --> 00:06:49.910
PETER KNIGHTS: Cue it up.

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:51.840
That's perfect.

00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:52.870
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:58.120
-What if you could see how
shark fin soup is made?

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:01.930
If you could see how each year
up to 70 million sharks are

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:07.355
killed to end up in soup,
could you still eat it?

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:12.850
A third of all shark species
are nearly extinct.

00:07:12.850 --> 00:07:15.260
But we can help save them.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:20.080
-Remember, when the buying
stops, the killing can too.

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:21.480
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:25.830
DIANE SOLINGER: So that's Yao
Ming, great Chinese and an

00:07:25.830 --> 00:07:28.220
American icon from the
Houston Rockets.

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:29.870
But that's in English.

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:31.240
How does that translate back?

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:32.890
PETER KNIGHTS: Well, everything
we do, anything you

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:34.490
see today has been
done in Mandarin.

00:07:34.490 --> 00:07:38.200
And the first ad you saw with
Maurice Greene, that was in

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:40.390
the lead up to the 2008
Beijing Olympics.

00:07:40.390 --> 00:07:45.640
So we recruited by the end 20
Olympic gold athletes, themed

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:49.440
it around the Olympics, and
managed to get out a massive

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:52.160
campaign around the Olympics in
China, which obviously the

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.660
Olympics is probably one of the
biggest events to happen

00:07:54.660 --> 00:07:56.050
in China ever.

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:59.550
And we got conservation, little
piece of it, which was

00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:02.460
by using the heroes that were
there, we got the message over

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:05.100
hopefully in an interesting and
inspiring way that wasn't

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:08.460
seen as being sort of critical
or punitive.

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:11.060
It's saying, hey, we've all got
to solve this together.

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:12.800
And that's partly the spirit
of the Olympics.

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:15.620
So we tried to embody
that around then.

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:18.700
Yao has been a major
spokesperson on

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:20.160
the shark fin campaign.

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:23.270
As you say, he's a huge star,
in more sense than one--

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:23.570
DIANE SOLINGER: He is.

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:24.850
PETER KNIGHTS: --in China.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:27.070
Having traveled around Africa
with him last year, I can tell

00:08:27.070 --> 00:08:29.930
you being seven foot six is not
easy, especially when you

00:08:29.930 --> 00:08:31.990
have to get into small planes
and things like that.

00:08:31.990 --> 00:08:34.770
But he's a fantastic guy,
and very smart.

00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:36.740
He's now actually doing
a history degree.

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:38.399
I don't know how many
professional athletes after

00:08:38.399 --> 00:08:41.549
their career go back and do
college again, but that's the

00:08:41.549 --> 00:08:42.799
kind of guy he is.

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:45.120
And he's been fantastic as a
spokesperson for the campaign,

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:47.220
and obviously hugely influential
in China.

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:48.780
DIANE SOLINGER: How has the
shark fin campaign made a

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:49.290
difference?

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:52.450
What's the before and after,
and is it still running?

00:08:52.450 --> 00:08:53.270
PETER KNIGHTS: It's
still running.

00:08:53.270 --> 00:08:56.160
I mean, somebody once said, a
very wise man once said, in

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:58.850
the environment, our victories
are temporary and our losses

00:08:58.850 --> 00:08:59.490
are permanent.

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:00.760
And I think that's very true.

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:02.560
So we can never give
up these things.

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:06.450
But we've seen consistently all
around the world how we've

00:09:06.450 --> 00:09:09.440
been able to reduce shark fin
consumption by about a third.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:11.790
We were sued in Thailand by
the shark fin traders for

00:09:11.790 --> 00:09:13.790
cutting their business by 50%.

00:09:13.790 --> 00:09:16.790
And most recently in 2012, the
Chinese government actually

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:19.300
banned shark fin from state
banquets, which is very

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:20.200
significant.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:23.830
And the data we're getting back
now is that in 2012, the

00:09:23.830 --> 00:09:26.795
shark fin trade was reduced
between 50% and 70%--

00:09:26.795 --> 00:09:27.090
DIANE SOLINGER: That's
tremendous.

00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:29.250
PETER KNIGHTS: --in China, which
is talking really tens

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:30.020
of millions of sharks.

00:09:30.020 --> 00:09:31.800
And we're getting messages back
from the field saying

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:33.760
that fisherman aren't going
out to catch the sharks

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:35.210
anymore because it's
not economic.

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:36.860
The fuel costs are too much.

00:09:36.860 --> 00:09:38.970
So that's the goal
in all these.

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:40.140
DIANE SOLINGER: This is
where you're economics

00:09:40.140 --> 00:09:41.040
degree came in handy.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:43.720
PETER KNIGHTS: I did remember
little bit of economics.

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:44.800
Some of it stayed there.

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:45.450
DIANE SOLINGER: Nice.

00:09:45.450 --> 00:09:47.160
PETER KNIGHTS: And what's really
different about WildAid

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:50.320
in our approach is most efforts
in conservation are

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:51.160
supply side.

00:09:51.160 --> 00:09:52.970
They're about trying to protect
the species in the

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.850
wild or study the species
or pass laws.

00:09:55.850 --> 00:09:58.030
Nobody was looking
at the demand.

00:09:58.030 --> 00:10:02.350
And my economics tell me if you
don't address the demand,

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:04.610
all you're necessarily going to
do by greater protection is

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:06.490
probably push up the price.

00:10:06.490 --> 00:10:10.150
And so, if you could reduce the
demand at the same time,

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:12.850
you reduce the economic
incentive to do the activity.

00:10:12.850 --> 00:10:15.380
Then that's got to be the
only-- frankly the only

00:10:15.380 --> 00:10:16.580
long-term solution to this.

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:19.810
And I think a lot of people
thought it may be impossible

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:20.830
to affect the demand.

00:10:20.830 --> 00:10:23.740
But what we've done is we've
used exactly the same tools

00:10:23.740 --> 00:10:26.780
that a commercial company would
use to promote a product

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:28.690
to stigmatize a product.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:34.400
So we've used top athletes,
movie stars, et cetera, as our

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:37.600
spokespeople just as a brand
might use a celebrity

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:38.570
spokesperson.

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:40.720
We've used high-end advertising
techniques.

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:42.760
We've use billboards,
television.

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:44.600
And we've been lucky enough in
China to have the support of

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:45.560
the Chinese government.

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:48.170
So all this stuff goes
out on state TV.

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:50.110
And in the United States,
you know public service

00:10:50.110 --> 00:10:51.720
announcement, you have to
be up at 3:00 AM in the

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:52.830
morning to see it.

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:54.470
But in China, we've been getting
these slots out.

00:10:54.470 --> 00:10:56.440
Like that slot with Yao
Ming has been out

00:10:56.440 --> 00:10:57.740
at 7 o'clock primetime.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:00.460
And somebody commented they've
seen it countless times.

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:03.670
So actually, in China, we're
able to get these out at the

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:06.590
same kind of level as a
commercial company would.

00:11:06.590 --> 00:11:09.250
So we are able to influence
a lot of different people.

00:11:09.250 --> 00:11:12.930
And when I go to China, I see
our ads in the back of the

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:14.570
taxi when I get out
of the airport.

00:11:14.570 --> 00:11:15.670
We see them in the airports.

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:17.570
We see them on the national
television.

00:11:17.570 --> 00:11:18.870
DIANE SOLINGER: How have you
managed to have that great

00:11:18.870 --> 00:11:21.100
relationship with
the government?

00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:24.980
PETER KNIGHTS: Well, I think
first of all, the Chinese

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:26.410
government wants to do
the right thing, a

00:11:26.410 --> 00:11:27.080
lot of these things.

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:29.790
It doesn't always get there,
as many governments don't.

00:11:29.790 --> 00:11:31.110
But they want to do
the right thing.

00:11:31.110 --> 00:11:32.700
And they've been--

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:35.800
last year we had over $200
million worth of free media

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:36.860
space from China.

00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:38.900
And I'd be surprised if
we could ever get

00:11:38.900 --> 00:11:40.950
that in the US, but--

00:11:40.950 --> 00:11:43.830
So there is a desire from people
in China to want to do

00:11:43.830 --> 00:11:44.560
something about this.

00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:46.440
A lot of people know
this is an issue.

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:48.330
You've got to remember with
something like rhino horn, for

00:11:48.330 --> 00:11:52.170
example, this is a minuscule
proportion of people in China

00:11:52.170 --> 00:11:53.790
that would consume rhino horn.

00:11:53.790 --> 00:11:55.160
The vast majority--

00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:58.840
we just did a survey and 95%
of people in China said the

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:00.440
government should do more
to help rhinos, and

00:12:00.440 --> 00:12:01.680
the same with elephants.

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:04.700
So as people get the education,
the awareness,

00:12:04.700 --> 00:12:07.340
there's been a tremendous
affinity, I think, in China.

00:12:07.340 --> 00:12:08.510
The people want to do
the right thing.

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:09.990
They want to be on
the right side.

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:13.970
And it's really just been
catalyzing that action.

00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:15.650
DIANE SOLINGER: Let's turn
the conversation to

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:16.590
elephants for a minute.

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:19.990
We'll run a short video on
elephants, I believe, and then

00:12:19.990 --> 00:12:22.710
we'll talk a little bit about
that and the demand for ivory.

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:23.187
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:23.187 --> 00:12:26.049
-Bigger.

00:12:26.049 --> 00:12:28.532
Stronger.

00:12:28.532 --> 00:12:31.295
And more domineering
than any other.

00:12:31.295 --> 00:12:33.980
Elephants are the centers
of the animal kingdom.

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:37.320
But unfortunately today,
they're under attack.

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:40.730
Tens of thousands are being
killed each year just for

00:12:40.730 --> 00:12:41.570
their ivory.

00:12:41.570 --> 00:12:45.260
So please, support conservation
and never buy

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:46.670
products made from ivory.

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:51.983
Because when the buying stops,
the killing can too.

00:12:51.983 --> 00:12:53.370
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:56.200
So NBA's tremendously
powerful in China, a

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:57.100
very popular sport.

00:12:57.100 --> 00:13:00.430
And with the elephants, I think,
we really look back as

00:13:00.430 --> 00:13:02.500
to it was the first thing
I really kind of

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:04.500
worked on back in 1989.

00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:06.680
And we were in a crisis with
elephants back in 1989.

00:13:06.680 --> 00:13:11.680
And some people are too young to
remember this, but prior to

00:13:11.680 --> 00:13:14.290
1989, ivory trade was legal

00:13:14.290 --> 00:13:15.810
internationally around the world.

00:13:15.810 --> 00:13:19.450
And under a system of regulated
trade, the elephant

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:23.240
numbers fell from 1.2 million
to 600,000 in 20 years.

00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:25.620
And so this regulated trade was
actually enabling massive

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:28.730
illegal activity to go on
through laundering processes.

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:31.200
And in 1989, there was
an international

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:32.560
ban on ivory trade.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:35.000
Essentially overnight, because
of all the publicity and the

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.110
awareness, the market in the
United States and Europe,

00:13:37.110 --> 00:13:40.060
which were significant markets,
collapsed completely.

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:42.430
And for about 15 or 20 years,
the African elephant was

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:43.190
actually doing fine.

00:13:43.190 --> 00:13:44.680
It was actually recovering.

00:13:44.680 --> 00:13:48.370
And then from about 2006, 2008
onwards, first of all, they

00:13:48.370 --> 00:13:52.060
allowed illegal sale of ivory
from Africa to China.

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:53.360
And then we just saw
the poaching

00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:54.600
going through the roof.

00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:59.150
And the two major factors I can
identify are, one, there

00:13:59.150 --> 00:14:01.560
is a much greater Asian, and
particularly Chinese, presence

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:03.840
in Africa now doing many
construction projects.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:07.240
So in some ways the market
has come to Africa.

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:09.800
But also the growth of the
Chinese economy has meant many

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:11.320
more people can afford it.

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:14.550
And these are people that back
in 1989 didn't have access to

00:14:14.550 --> 00:14:16.870
international media and
certainly didn't have access

00:14:16.870 --> 00:14:18.450
to the kind of money
to buy ivory.

00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:21.470
So you've got a new
wave of consumer--

00:14:21.470 --> 00:14:21.700
DIANE SOLINGER: New consumers.

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:22.060
PETER KNIGHTS: --if you like.

00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:22.630
DIANE SOLINGER: Yeah.

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:24.230
PETER KNIGHTS: --which
is now driving

00:14:24.230 --> 00:14:25.750
this poaching academic.

00:14:25.750 --> 00:14:29.570
And so, again, every time I've
seen these poaching things get

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:32.165
bad, it correlates with
an expansion in

00:14:32.165 --> 00:14:33.890
the consuming market.

00:14:33.890 --> 00:14:38.160
So back in the 1970s and '80s,
there was a market for rhino

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:40.560
horns as dagger handles
in the Yemen.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.900
And when there was the oil
boom of '73 and a lot of

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:45.770
Yemenis working the Saudi
oil fields, suddenly

00:14:45.770 --> 00:14:47.720
that market went up.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:49.630
So when it gets back to it to
me, it's all about economics.

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:50.930
It's not about biology.

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:52.150
And unfortunately, it's
not about laws.

00:14:52.150 --> 00:14:53.100
It's about economics.

00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:53.510
And the only--

00:14:53.510 --> 00:14:54.850
DIANE SOLINGER: Well, it's
making things that people

00:14:54.850 --> 00:14:58.730
think are prized and special
or elite when you have the

00:14:58.730 --> 00:14:59.920
economic power to buy that.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:02.410
You have to, like you said,
stigmatize them and make them

00:15:02.410 --> 00:15:03.370
not cool anymore.

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:03.950
PETER KNIGHTS: Exactly.

00:15:03.950 --> 00:15:08.160
Because 15 years ago, the only
people in China able to afford

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:10.830
shark fin soup would be
government officials, frankly.

00:15:10.830 --> 00:15:12.340
Now there are many
more people.

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:14.970
I mean we did a survey, and it
looked like up to 100 million

00:15:14.970 --> 00:15:17.200
people in China were consuming
shark fin soup.

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:20.520
So although this is a
traditional product, it was

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:22.760
never traditional to consume
on these levels.

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:25.060
And that's the essence of most
of these problems is these are

00:15:25.060 --> 00:15:27.910
things which have some cultural
history, but were

00:15:27.910 --> 00:15:28.965
always done on a tiny scale.

00:15:28.965 --> 00:15:30.710
It was the thing kings
and lords could do.

00:15:30.710 --> 00:15:32.450
And now it's everyone
can do it.

00:15:32.450 --> 00:15:34.640
And it's much easier to ship
things around the world now,

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:36.410
globalization.

00:15:36.410 --> 00:15:39.810
People FedEx some of these
things sometimes, scarily.

00:15:39.810 --> 00:15:45.030
So we've got to cope with a new
era, and media is part of

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:45.980
coping with that era, I think.

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:47.950
DIANE SOLINGER: Right.

00:15:47.950 --> 00:15:50.971
How do you see these
things picked up?

00:15:50.971 --> 00:15:56.750
With the ivory trade you've
seen through the media

00:15:56.750 --> 00:15:59.120
campaign you're making a big
difference in that, but how

00:15:59.120 --> 00:16:01.420
does that get spread outside
of the channels that you're

00:16:01.420 --> 00:16:03.900
using, the traditional
media channels--

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:06.005
YouTube, here we are--

00:16:06.005 --> 00:16:08.590
how do these stories get spread
more and more so it

00:16:08.590 --> 00:16:10.160
becomes this ubiquitous
thought?

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:11.430
We don't do this.

00:16:11.430 --> 00:16:12.250
I don't buy that.

00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:13.500
PETER KNIGHTS: No,
and it does.

00:16:15.510 --> 00:16:16.260
It's always interesting.

00:16:16.260 --> 00:16:18.750
We did a lot of work,
conventional media, with Yao,

00:16:18.750 --> 00:16:19.250
for example.

00:16:19.250 --> 00:16:21.130
We do a press conference.

00:16:21.130 --> 00:16:24.170
By serendipity, there's a few
things that happened in the

00:16:24.170 --> 00:16:26.720
history that kind of played into
our hands in some ways,

00:16:26.720 --> 00:16:29.440
but Yao Ming's first team was
called the Shanghai Sharks.

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:31.810
And when he retired, he bought
the Shanghai Sharks.

00:16:31.810 --> 00:16:34.660
So we had Yao saves the
sharks, literally and

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:36.002
metaphorically.

00:16:36.002 --> 00:16:40.500
But every time we've done this,
there's an explosion of

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:43.270
activity on the micro blogs in
China, which is one of the

00:16:43.270 --> 00:16:44.610
premium mediums.

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:47.290
My understanding is one of the
big differences in China

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:50.070
between social media is a lot
of it is cellphone based.

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:53.010
A lot of people still don't
have good internet

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:54.290
connections.

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:58.170
And also this tends to be like
the micro blog, some extended

00:16:58.170 --> 00:17:00.030
Twitter type thing, which
gets the word out.

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:02.670
And so, we've had an
overwhelmingly positive

00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:05.770
reaction from the younger
audience.

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:10.520
And how that feeds back I've
seen so many times is that CNN

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:11.910
did a piece on the shark
fin campaign.

00:17:11.910 --> 00:17:13.650
And they had the shark fin
traders, I've been in the

00:17:13.650 --> 00:17:15.440
business for 50 years,
and my future's

00:17:15.440 --> 00:17:16.420
never looked so gloomy.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:18.920
And it said at the end, but he
doesn't eat shark fin soup

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:20.050
anymore, because his
grandchildren

00:17:20.050 --> 00:17:21.270
asked him not to.

00:17:21.270 --> 00:17:23.480
So even the guy selling it
will not eat it anymore

00:17:23.480 --> 00:17:25.480
because of the influence
of his grandchildren.

00:17:25.480 --> 00:17:28.830
And so I think social media
is very, very important.

00:17:28.830 --> 00:17:32.070
We tend to seed things through
conventional media,

00:17:32.070 --> 00:17:35.680
particularly because if you
get on CCTV1, you have the

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:37.420
weight and support of the
government implicitly.

00:17:37.420 --> 00:17:39.960
So that means everyone knows
like, OK, so the government's

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:41.500
on board with this.

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:43.530
And the interesting thing I find
in China is that although

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:46.780
people talk about political
censorship and things, on the

00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:49.290
environment, there's been a
fantastic amount of debate.

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:51.510
And the government seems to have
decided the environment

00:17:51.510 --> 00:17:53.480
is a legitimate place
for people to

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:55.160
express their feelings.

00:17:55.160 --> 00:17:57.510
And so you see a lot of quite
critical pieces on the

00:17:57.510 --> 00:18:00.250
environment in China, and
largely through social media.

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:04.260
So we do have pretty good
relationships with [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:04.260 --> 00:18:05.640
.com over there.

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:07.910
It has covered our Yao Ming
story exclusively,

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:08.860
and helps with that.

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:12.810
Also QQ, which is the instant
messaging, who, I think, has

00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:14.490
something like 700 million
subscribers

00:18:14.490 --> 00:18:16.120
or some crazy number.

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:17.940
And we have a microsite
on their website.

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:20.590
So we're going to be using
social media more and more as

00:18:20.590 --> 00:18:22.230
we've been able to build
up our staff presence.

00:18:22.230 --> 00:18:23.980
But it's very important.

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:27.160
And everything I see is an
incredible support for these

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:28.810
movements on the internet.

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:30.470
DIANE SOLINGER: And you
mentioned China, and when we

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:32.630
were talking earlier, if you're
not playing in China

00:18:32.630 --> 00:18:35.830
given the new consumer market,
you really aren't going to

00:18:35.830 --> 00:18:36.760
address this at all.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:38.870
But what are other countries
or other parts of the world

00:18:38.870 --> 00:18:41.310
that WildAid is really taking
a deep dive into?

00:18:41.310 --> 00:18:42.610
PETER KNIGHTS: Well, we've
done a lot of work

00:18:42.610 --> 00:18:44.000
consistently in Southeast
Asia.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:45.970
And again, one of the other
things that gives me hope is

00:18:45.970 --> 00:18:49.250
we did a lot of work with the
rhinos, for example, in

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:51.940
Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Singapore
when those countries

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:56.220
where the problems, because
that's where the money was.

00:18:56.220 --> 00:18:59.620
And the Clinton administration
sanctioned Taiwan over rhino

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:00.580
horn trade.

00:19:00.580 --> 00:19:03.210
And for 20 years, the rhinos
were doing well, and they were

00:19:03.210 --> 00:19:04.080
increasing.

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:06.710
So we did manage to basically
suppress and close down the

00:19:06.710 --> 00:19:09.210
market in Singapore, Hong
Kong, and Taiwan.

00:19:09.210 --> 00:19:10.860
But a new market emerged,
which was

00:19:10.860 --> 00:19:13.290
Vietnam now and China.

00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:15.880
And so we've got to go around
and redo that same job again

00:19:15.880 --> 00:19:16.710
now with these new countries.

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:18.690
But I look back and
I say, look, this

00:19:18.690 --> 00:19:20.200
worked for 20 years.

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:21.650
Because some people say, well,
you know what, bans don't

00:19:21.650 --> 00:19:23.640
work, and it doesn't happen.

00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:26.490
It's like, bans without
education don't work.

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:28.360
If people understand why
something is banned and

00:19:28.360 --> 00:19:30.460
they're sympathetic to
it, then a ban can

00:19:30.460 --> 00:19:31.170
be very, very effect.

00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:32.370
DIANE SOLINGER: Well, it's just
like telling somebody you

00:19:32.370 --> 00:19:35.750
can't have that, and then you
want it more sometimes maybe.

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:36.210
PETER KNIGHTS: Potentially.

00:19:36.210 --> 00:19:37.510
It all depends on the process.

00:19:37.510 --> 00:19:38.880
DIANE SOLINGER: If they
understand why--

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:39.665
PETER KNIGHTS: Exactly.

00:19:39.665 --> 00:19:41.990
And the process for the ivory
trade ban was that it had

00:19:41.990 --> 00:19:42.770
international media.

00:19:42.770 --> 00:19:44.520
Everyone was seeing poached
elephants everywhere.

00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:46.180
And everyone was like, oh,
this really sucks.

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:47.720
I didn't realize that's
how ivory comes.

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:49.950
They don't do it anymore.

00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:52.610
So we've seen successful periods
of conservation with

00:19:52.610 --> 00:19:54.070
both the elephants and rhinos.

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:55.450
And then we've seen
when a new market

00:19:55.450 --> 00:19:57.830
emerges, it causes problems.

00:19:57.830 --> 00:19:59.460
So you kind of have to
counter those things.

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:02.500
So Southeast Asia has been
very important to us.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:03.380
We've done campaigns.

00:20:03.380 --> 00:20:05.390
You know, you may have heard a
couple of years ago here we

00:20:05.390 --> 00:20:07.255
got shark fin banned
in California.

00:20:07.255 --> 00:20:07.930
DIANE SOLINGER: Right.

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:09.580
PETER KNIGHTS: And people said
at the time, well, California

00:20:09.580 --> 00:20:11.350
is a relatively small market.

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:13.010
And my argument was, yes,
but you know what?

00:20:13.010 --> 00:20:14.600
It's a very influential
market.

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:17.090
And people look to California
to see what are the new

00:20:17.090 --> 00:20:18.380
environmental things
that are happening.

00:20:18.380 --> 00:20:20.870
And I'm pretty certain that
that California ban was

00:20:20.870 --> 00:20:23.260
influential in those people
giving up shark fin

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:26.940
in China, as well.

00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:29.630
DIANE SOLINGER: So talk
about rhinos a bit.

00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:32.010
Let's run the rhino PSA.

00:20:32.010 --> 00:20:34.896
And this one might be a little
sensitive for people, to just

00:20:34.896 --> 00:20:36.784
let you know.

00:20:36.784 --> 00:20:37.190
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:20:37.190 --> 00:21:05.721
-[SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

00:21:05.721 --> 00:21:06.220
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:06.660
DIANE SOLINGER: I love it.

00:21:06.660 --> 00:21:08.460
When buying stops, the
killing stops.

00:21:08.460 --> 00:21:09.590
It's a great tag line.

00:21:09.590 --> 00:21:10.160
PETER KNIGHTS: Very
simple idea.

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:14.150
In Chinese, it's actually just
no buying, no killing.

00:21:14.150 --> 00:21:17.980
And I actually was in China
recently with a very senior

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:19.370
government official, and
he said to me, he

00:21:19.370 --> 00:21:19.940
said, you know what?

00:21:19.940 --> 00:21:21.580
Because of all this stuff,
everybody in

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:23.050
China knows your slogan.

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:25.820
I said, well, that's very, very
kind of you, but I don't

00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:27.230
really think that's the case.

00:21:27.230 --> 00:21:29.000
And he called over the waiter,
and he said, what's the slogan

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:29.515
about conservation?

00:21:29.515 --> 00:21:31.170
And the waiter trots
out this slogan.

00:21:31.170 --> 00:21:34.420
And one of my other colleagues
was right out in this sort of

00:21:34.420 --> 00:21:37.050
very rural area, and she said,
oh, I saw you're Yao Ming

00:21:37.050 --> 00:21:37.860
thing going out there.

00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:41.460
So the Chinese government's
distribution network reaches

00:21:41.460 --> 00:21:43.000
everybody through CCTV.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.800
And they've been one of our main
sponsors and supporters.

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:48.450
And people now are using the
slogan without saying anything

00:21:48.450 --> 00:21:49.580
about WildAid, which is great.

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:52.960
So Chinese TV was saying,
when the buying stops,

00:21:52.960 --> 00:21:53.840
the killing can too.

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:56.410
It's become bit of a mantra,
which is fantastic.

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:57.340
DIANE SOLINGER: It's
not about WildAid.

00:21:57.340 --> 00:21:58.130
It's about getting--

00:21:58.130 --> 00:21:58.580
PETER KNIGHTS: Absolutely.

00:21:58.580 --> 00:21:58.780
And that's--

00:21:58.780 --> 00:21:59.080
DIANE SOLINGER: --it to stop.

00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:00.630
PETER KNIGHTS: --always what we
said right from the start

00:22:00.630 --> 00:22:03.480
is like when we got all this
free media space and things.

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:06.010
First of all, we didn't even
have a name on it, because we

00:22:06.010 --> 00:22:07.040
said it's not about us.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:07.600
It's not about us.

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:08.630
It's not about branding.

00:22:08.630 --> 00:22:09.790
This is not about us
raising money.

00:22:09.790 --> 00:22:11.560
It's about attitudinal change.

00:22:11.560 --> 00:22:14.550
And so, I think that's been key
to what we've been able to

00:22:14.550 --> 00:22:16.540
do is we have been prepared to
say, we'll step back as an

00:22:16.540 --> 00:22:17.760
organization--

00:22:17.760 --> 00:22:20.170
suicide for fundraising
probably, but in terms of

00:22:20.170 --> 00:22:23.980
getting people to accept the
ideas as their own and they'll

00:22:23.980 --> 00:22:25.950
participate, and definitely
the right way to go.

00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:27.390
DIANE SOLINGER: Well, you're
building a social movement,

00:22:27.390 --> 00:22:29.050
not just building an
organization, and that's a

00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:31.805
bigger mission, right?

00:22:31.805 --> 00:22:34.450
PETER KNIGHTS: Yeah.

00:22:34.450 --> 00:22:37.700
DIANE SOLINGER: I'm naive
on rhino horn.

00:22:37.700 --> 00:22:39.330
What is it used for?

00:22:39.330 --> 00:22:41.850
PETER KNIGHTS: Well, it's been
used in traditional medicine

00:22:41.850 --> 00:22:44.720
as a fever reducer as part
of traditional medicine.

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:48.380
And a lot of people say, well,
traditional medicine, BS.

00:22:48.380 --> 00:22:51.550
There is a lot of traditional
medicine which has roots.

00:22:51.550 --> 00:22:52.930
I mean a lot of Western medicine
is derived from

00:22:52.930 --> 00:22:54.640
natural sources.

00:22:54.640 --> 00:22:58.040
But with rhino horn, it has
been thoroughly tested.

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:01.560
And the only property it's been
seen to have is in very

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:04.160
large quantities it reduces
fever mildly.

00:23:04.160 --> 00:23:06.380
So the pharmaceutical companies
in the West decided

00:23:06.380 --> 00:23:09.075
there's nothing really worth
pursuing in here.

00:23:09.075 --> 00:23:11.240
But that was the traditional
use.

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:13.610
But what we find now-- we've
just done a survey, so I can

00:23:13.610 --> 00:23:17.130
say this with some authority--
that people believe that it

00:23:17.130 --> 00:23:18.200
can be an aphrodisiac.

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:20.495
They believe in some
cases it's a

00:23:20.495 --> 00:23:22.160
hangover cure in Vietnam.

00:23:22.160 --> 00:23:24.030
So we've actually gone-- and
some people even believe it

00:23:24.030 --> 00:23:24.700
cures cancer.

00:23:24.700 --> 00:23:26.310
And basically, rhino
horn is carotene.

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:27.490
It's what you're fingernails
are made of.

00:23:27.490 --> 00:23:28.490
It's what your hair
is made of.

00:23:28.490 --> 00:23:30.740
It's actually made of
compressed, matted hair.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:34.570
And so, there's an element
of snake oil

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:36.270
in all of this stuff.

00:23:36.270 --> 00:23:40.300
And again, this is sort of
when you're talking about

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:43.530
faith-based medicine, it's quite
hard to get around that.

00:23:43.530 --> 00:23:45.205
So we don't usually take
it on by saying,

00:23:45.205 --> 00:23:46.570
oh, it doesn't work.

00:23:46.570 --> 00:23:48.760
We usually try instead to appeal
to people's better

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:51.580
sense of look at what you're
causing to happen.

00:23:51.580 --> 00:23:56.440
And that rhino there, Thandi,
the story now is that because

00:23:56.440 --> 00:23:59.060
if you shoot a rhino,
there's a gunshot.

00:23:59.060 --> 00:24:00.920
And what they've been doing
now is using tranquilizer

00:24:00.920 --> 00:24:04.750
darts which are silent, cutting
the face off the rhino

00:24:04.750 --> 00:24:08.480
while it's still alive just
to get these horns.

00:24:08.480 --> 00:24:11.160
And they could actually take
the horn off and leave the

00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:11.800
rhino alive.

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:14.296
But they want to get every bit
of rhino horn so they take the

00:24:14.296 --> 00:24:15.010
whole face off.

00:24:15.010 --> 00:24:18.090
And Thandi is actually one of
the few rhinos that survived

00:24:18.090 --> 00:24:18.840
that process.

00:24:18.840 --> 00:24:20.968
But it's horrible
what's going on.

00:24:20.968 --> 00:24:22.920
DIANE SOLINGER: Right.

00:24:22.920 --> 00:24:25.690
And explain the habitat
for the rhino.

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:26.795
Where does Thandi live?

00:24:26.795 --> 00:24:29.070
PETER KNIGHTS: Thandi lives
in South Africa.

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:30.770
For most endangered species,
the biggest

00:24:30.770 --> 00:24:32.340
threat is habitat loss.

00:24:32.340 --> 00:24:33.130
They're running out of space.

00:24:33.130 --> 00:24:35.350
Human beings are taking over
the land for agriculture.

00:24:35.350 --> 00:24:36.780
With rhinos, there
is absolutely

00:24:36.780 --> 00:24:38.460
no shortage of habitat.

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:40.280
We could quite easily
accommodate

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:42.080
300,000 or 400,000 rhinos.

00:24:42.080 --> 00:24:46.020
And yet, there's about 27,000,
30,000 left just

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:47.360
because of the horn.

00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:49.100
So there's no shortage.

00:24:49.100 --> 00:24:51.810
And the last rhino in Vietnam
was poached in

00:24:51.810 --> 00:24:53.210
2011, I think it was.

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:54.220
DIANE SOLINGER: No more there?

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:54.410
PETER KNIGHTS: No more.

00:24:54.410 --> 00:24:56.530
Well, most of the Asian rhinos,
they're down to like

00:24:56.530 --> 00:24:58.870
50 or 100 of the two
species now.

00:24:58.870 --> 00:25:01.670
Having said that, the white
rhino, which Thandi is one of

00:25:01.670 --> 00:25:05.060
them, came back from 50
individuals to 22,000.

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:07.360
So again, this is a
reason for hope.

00:25:07.360 --> 00:25:09.950
When they're not being poached
for their horn, we can bring

00:25:09.950 --> 00:25:12.670
them back into significant
numbers.

00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:15.370
So we really do have to
address this problem.

00:25:15.370 --> 00:25:17.100
Otherwise, we won't succeed.

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:21.820
But I'm optimistic that if we
can address the trade issue, a

00:25:21.820 --> 00:25:23.850
lot of these animals can
bounce back to decent

00:25:23.850 --> 00:25:25.000
populations.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:26.840
DIANE SOLINGER: We touched on
a few of the animals that

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:29.720
you're working to try to
bring awareness to.

00:25:29.720 --> 00:25:32.190
What other areas of
focus do you have?

00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:33.040
PETER KNIGHTS: We're
working on tigers

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:34.280
and a few other species.

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:37.500
But as an organization, we're
actually starting work on

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:39.170
climate change as well.

00:25:39.170 --> 00:25:42.160
Because what we're about is
behavior change, communication

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:44.810
for behavior change, attitudinal
behavior change.

00:25:44.810 --> 00:25:47.240
And many of these animals will
be threatened by climate

00:25:47.240 --> 00:25:49.820
change, as well as us
in different ways.

00:25:49.820 --> 00:25:52.240
And because of our presence
in China as well as our

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:53.010
connections to China.

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:55.480
In fact, the Chinese government
came to us-- a very

00:25:55.480 --> 00:25:58.400
senior person in China came to
us and said, we love what

00:25:58.400 --> 00:26:00.850
you're doing with wildlife
trade, but our bigger problem

00:26:00.850 --> 00:26:01.340
is climate.

00:26:01.340 --> 00:26:03.530
Will you help us work
on the climate?

00:26:03.530 --> 00:26:03.980
So--

00:26:03.980 --> 00:26:05.780
DIANE SOLINGER: Similar form
of campaign structure?

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:06.500
PETER KNIGHTS: Exactly.

00:26:06.500 --> 00:26:09.030
Same kind of campaign to
sensitize people in China to

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:11.570
what they can do about
mitigating climate change.

00:26:11.570 --> 00:26:16.210
And I said, you know, wow,
yes, we'd love to.

00:26:16.210 --> 00:26:18.000
Its hard for us to finance
it because we're

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:18.880
not from that world.

00:26:18.880 --> 00:26:21.500
But basically, the techniques
we have I think are

00:26:21.500 --> 00:26:22.480
applicable.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:24.590
And so we just starting
that campaign now.

00:26:24.590 --> 00:26:26.750
And the government's giving
us full backing.

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:30.080
And then the other area we work
on is marine protection.

00:26:30.080 --> 00:26:31.480
And again, we looked
at what are the

00:26:31.480 --> 00:26:33.060
gaps, what's not happening.

00:26:33.060 --> 00:26:36.340
And we've been, I think,
instrumental on trying to use

00:26:36.340 --> 00:26:39.050
new technology to protect
marine areas.

00:26:39.050 --> 00:26:41.900
And the biggest challenge for
this thing, one is resources.

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:44.552
But the Galapagos Marine Reserve
we work in, it's the

00:26:44.552 --> 00:26:47.390
size of New York state,
massive area.

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:51.020
Boats are slow, very expensive
to maintain, believe me.

00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:53.790
Ever want to lose money,
buy yourself a boat.

00:26:53.790 --> 00:26:56.150
Maintenance, fuel, et cetera,
is very expensive.

00:26:56.150 --> 00:26:57.950
But the new technology is
getting beyond that.

00:26:57.950 --> 00:27:00.700
So one of the things we're
employing is satellite vessel

00:27:00.700 --> 00:27:01.610
monitoring.

00:27:01.610 --> 00:27:04.120
So this uses satellite to
basically track the boats in

00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:06.870
the same way that air traffic
control uses transponders.

00:27:06.870 --> 00:27:08.290
So you can see what the
boat is, how fast

00:27:08.290 --> 00:27:09.970
it's going, what direction.

00:27:09.970 --> 00:27:13.920
And now, we don't need a big
boat to be out at sea trying

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:14.720
to find these people.

00:27:14.720 --> 00:27:16.420
We have them on a
radar screen.

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:19.290
And basically, you can even
program it so that it

00:27:19.290 --> 00:27:21.310
recognizes fishing behavior.

00:27:21.310 --> 00:27:22.420
A boat does a certain thing
when it fishes.

00:27:22.420 --> 00:27:23.820
It stops, it puts out a line.

00:27:23.820 --> 00:27:24.630
There's a pattern.

00:27:24.630 --> 00:27:27.440
So we actually have a situation
now where a guy in

00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:29.480
Galapagos is basically sitting
at a computer screen.

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:32.900
He can be enjoying a beer in
the bar, and his cell phone

00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:34.650
will tell you, oops, we've
got a problem.

00:27:34.650 --> 00:27:36.890
And you can see exactly where
it is, what's going on.

00:27:36.890 --> 00:27:38.620
You send a small boat
to intercept it.

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:40.900
So you're literally saving
millions of dollars a year and

00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:42.520
having really good coverage.

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:44.540
And so now what we see in
Galapagos is right around the

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:46.290
border of the marine reserve,
all these fishing boats are

00:27:46.290 --> 00:27:48.330
queued up, literally
on the border.

00:27:48.330 --> 00:27:49.810
You can draw the border of
the marine reserve by

00:27:49.810 --> 00:27:50.300
where the boats are.

00:27:50.300 --> 00:27:51.350
DIANE SOLINGER: They know
they can't come in.

00:27:51.350 --> 00:27:52.300
PETER KNIGHTS: They know
they can't come in.

00:27:52.300 --> 00:27:54.060
If they come in, they're
going to get caught.

00:27:54.060 --> 00:27:56.590
So that's making marine
protection of these areas more

00:27:56.590 --> 00:27:58.550
and more affordable.

00:27:58.550 --> 00:28:00.656
And even technology like drones
is being used in this

00:28:00.656 --> 00:28:01.410
sort of stuff now.

00:28:01.410 --> 00:28:03.730
So suddenly marine protected
areas, which really are the

00:28:03.730 --> 00:28:04.910
poor cousin.

00:28:04.910 --> 00:28:07.320
You know, a national park system
is the backbone of

00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:08.570
conservational land.

00:28:08.570 --> 00:28:11.110
DIANE SOLINGER: But it's such
an arbitrary line, right.

00:28:11.110 --> 00:28:12.210
Who's out there policing it?

00:28:12.210 --> 00:28:13.100
PETER KNIGHTS: Well,
that's it.

00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:15.920
But we got to get more-- right
now, it's about 1% of the

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:17.600
world's oceans are marine
protected areas.

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:19.400
And it needs to be more
like 10 or 15.

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:22.040
But one of the arguments
against it was we can't

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:22.490
protect it.

00:28:22.490 --> 00:28:23.500
We can't enforce it.

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:25.396
New technology is helping
to solve that.

00:28:25.396 --> 00:28:28.640
DIANE SOLINGER: That's
fantastic.

