00:34:31.929 --> 00:34:33.199
on in China.

00:34:33.199 --> 00:34:34.510
And people need encouragement.

00:34:34.510 --> 00:34:36.179
When they're doing stuff,
they need encouragement.

00:34:36.179 --> 00:34:39.820
And so I hope that Yao
would inspire others.

00:34:39.820 --> 00:34:41.420
And certainly, he was inspired
by Jackie Chan in that

00:34:41.420 --> 00:34:42.150
campaign before.

00:34:42.150 --> 00:34:43.350
So that was nice.

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:44.679
That was sort of a generation
handover.

00:34:44.679 --> 00:34:46.489
We hope we can keep
to doing that.

00:34:46.489 --> 00:34:49.480
DIANE SOLINGER: Well, and the
idea that I find so compelling

00:34:49.480 --> 00:34:51.540
is that the message is clear.

00:34:51.540 --> 00:34:54.010
And there's an actionable step
that somebody can do.

00:34:54.010 --> 00:34:55.570
It's don't buy that.

00:34:55.570 --> 00:34:56.840
Make that decision.

00:34:56.840 --> 00:34:57.840
You're a consumer now.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:34:58.980
Make this choice.

00:34:58.980 --> 00:35:01.420
So we've seen that work.

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:04.520
You mentioned the younger
generation affecting and

00:35:04.520 --> 00:35:07.320
causing behavioral change in
older generations, as well.

00:35:07.320 --> 00:35:11.100
Remember back even back
in the smoking area.

00:35:11.100 --> 00:35:13.270
PETER KNIGHTS: Smoking's the
classic example where kids

00:35:13.270 --> 00:35:14.350
have influenced the parents.

00:35:14.350 --> 00:35:15.700
DIANE SOLINGER: I used to go
around and tell my grandpa,

00:35:15.700 --> 00:35:16.790
you know, cut it out.

00:35:16.790 --> 00:35:17.675
And so--

00:35:17.675 --> 00:35:19.040
PETER KNIGHTS: It's
hard to argue.

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:22.570
DIANE SOLINGER: Yeah it
does float back up.

00:35:22.570 --> 00:35:23.430
It's terrific.

00:35:23.430 --> 00:35:25.160
Thank you for sharing
how you're doing it.

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:27.970
And this is a different way
than a lot of wildlife

00:35:27.970 --> 00:35:30.630
organizations are attacking
these problems.

00:35:30.630 --> 00:35:31.400
I mean it is bold.

00:35:31.400 --> 00:35:32.630
It's in your face.

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:34.090
But it's giving you something
that you can do.

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:35.420
You can make a choice.

00:35:35.420 --> 00:35:39.400
And interesting way of doing it,
but what you're saying is

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:41.250
you're doing it differently
than others on purpose,

00:35:41.250 --> 00:35:43.500
because you're dealing with the
consumer side, with the

00:35:43.500 --> 00:35:44.370
buyer side.

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:46.570
And most are dealing with
the other side.

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:48.520
So I think together, you know,
put it together, what a

00:35:48.520 --> 00:35:52.450
powerful opportunity to really
save some of the world's most

00:35:52.450 --> 00:35:54.822
precious species.

00:35:54.822 --> 00:35:58.310
I'd like to open it up to some
questions from the folks here

00:35:58.310 --> 00:35:59.470
at YouTube.

00:35:59.470 --> 00:36:01.870
Anybody have anything they'd
like to ask Peter?

00:36:01.870 --> 00:36:03.610
AUDIENCE: So I'm very impressed
with all the work

00:36:03.610 --> 00:36:04.400
that you've done.

00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:08.200
And I was curious more about how
it sounded like a lot of

00:36:08.200 --> 00:36:12.930
the problems were more reactive
in terms of like

00:36:12.930 --> 00:36:13.820
here's a problem.

00:36:13.820 --> 00:36:14.920
Let's go and fix it now.

00:36:14.920 --> 00:36:17.910
And then it would come
back and do it again.

00:36:17.910 --> 00:36:21.480
How are you leveraging
technology to be a bit more

00:36:21.480 --> 00:36:24.720
proactive about future problems
that can arise?

00:36:24.720 --> 00:36:27.540
PETER KNIGHTS: To be honest, the
problem is not predicting.

00:36:27.540 --> 00:36:30.080
The problem is getting
work financed.

00:36:30.080 --> 00:36:34.350
And so, we only just started the
elephant-rhino campaigns

00:36:34.350 --> 00:36:36.550
because I've only just
got it financed.

00:36:36.550 --> 00:36:40.440
And I can tell you right now
that every species that's in

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:42.210
trade should have some
type of campaign

00:36:42.210 --> 00:36:44.380
like this, in my opinion.

00:36:44.380 --> 00:36:48.220
And the sharks, to a large
degree, not many sharks are

00:36:48.220 --> 00:36:49.720
classified as endangered yet.

00:36:49.720 --> 00:36:51.020
They're all heading that way.

00:36:51.020 --> 00:36:53.480
So in many ways that was our
predictive campaign, was to

00:36:53.480 --> 00:36:55.120
say if we don't carry
on like this.

00:36:55.120 --> 00:36:56.130
The other element that
was predictive

00:36:56.130 --> 00:36:57.500
is working in China.

00:36:57.500 --> 00:37:02.470
And there isn't another China
in terms of wildlife

00:37:02.470 --> 00:37:03.320
consumption.

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:05.900
There are smaller countries,
like some of the Southeast

00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:07.520
Asian countries, which
will grow, like

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:09.470
Vietnam's come out there.

00:37:09.470 --> 00:37:12.530
But the problem with being
predictive in this business,

00:37:12.530 --> 00:37:16.630
unfortunately, is resources.

00:37:16.630 --> 00:37:19.290
We're having a hard time funding
this now, because it's

00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:19.990
not conventional.

00:37:19.990 --> 00:37:21.710
It's not the conventional
approach.

00:37:21.710 --> 00:37:25.820
So there's probably between $50
and $100 million spent at

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:28.730
the supply end for rhinos
or elephants every year.

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:31.540
And until recently, there's
been nothing

00:37:31.540 --> 00:37:32.260
spent on the demand.

00:37:32.260 --> 00:37:34.260
And then now there's about
$300,000 or $400,000.

00:37:34.260 --> 00:37:38.700
So it's been very hard to even
be on the crisis, let alone

00:37:38.700 --> 00:37:39.670
ahead of the curve on this.

00:37:39.670 --> 00:37:42.770
But my dream for all this,
and now many other--

00:37:42.770 --> 00:37:47.490
I was in DC yesterday, and the
Fish and Wildlife Service

00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:49.330
there, they were all talking
about demand reduction now.

00:37:49.330 --> 00:37:50.250
So it's starting to become more

00:37:50.250 --> 00:37:52.160
mainstream in people's thinking.

00:37:52.160 --> 00:37:54.770
And so I'm hopeful that going
forward we can have something

00:37:54.770 --> 00:37:57.880
which is much more proactive
and more predictive.

00:37:57.880 --> 00:38:00.990
So when the International
Endangered Species List,

00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:04.380
[INAUDIBLE], puts a species on
that list, in my opinion there

00:38:04.380 --> 00:38:07.350
needs to be a campaign
to publicize that.

00:38:07.350 --> 00:38:09.550
And that would be my goal
is to have these kind of

00:38:09.550 --> 00:38:12.000
campaigns running all of the
places they need to be

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:14.700
running, but also to be looking
at what's the next

00:38:14.700 --> 00:38:17.150
problem going to be and
let's head it off.

00:38:17.150 --> 00:38:19.270
Having said that, I do think
that the campaign--

00:38:19.270 --> 00:38:21.580
we featured many different
animals and I think--

00:38:21.580 --> 00:38:23.210
it's almost like a brand.

00:38:23.210 --> 00:38:26.620
You're trying to go beyond
the individual message.

00:38:26.620 --> 00:38:29.800
So now the slogan, I hope with
the elephant campaign, people

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:32.390
be like, well, this is
just like the sharks.

00:38:32.390 --> 00:38:35.630
These animals have been killed
for pretty senseless use.

00:38:35.630 --> 00:38:37.960
And there's too many
people buying it.

00:38:37.960 --> 00:38:39.190
As you say, the reaction's
the same.

00:38:39.190 --> 00:38:41.340
Don't buy it, or tell other
people not to buy it.

00:38:41.340 --> 00:38:43.950
So I hope we're being somewhat
predictive in terms of now

00:38:43.950 --> 00:38:46.680
setting a precedent out there
where other species come up.

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:48.760
People are already, OK, we
recognize this problem.

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:51.080
We know what we have
to do about it.

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:53.980
AUDIENCE: I would imagine that
really looking at partnerships

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:58.280
with technology companies to
leverage technology to

00:38:58.280 --> 00:39:02.840
predicting fever outbreaks and
looking for technology

00:39:02.840 --> 00:39:05.050
partners to scale--

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:06.480
PETER KNIGHTS: I'm not sure the
prediction thing is that

00:39:06.480 --> 00:39:07.120
complicated.

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:09.890
I could tell you now the
countries that-- you just look

00:39:09.890 --> 00:39:11.300
at where the economics
are going.

00:39:11.300 --> 00:39:13.580
And so you look at any country
that's rising economically

00:39:13.580 --> 00:39:16.650
that has some history of this
use, and you say, that may be

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:17.680
a problem for us.

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:20.510
Where I think technology and
the companies can help is

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:22.620
getting the message out and
getting the message out

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:23.170
creatively.

00:39:23.170 --> 00:39:24.705
I mean we were talking
before about--

00:39:24.705 --> 00:39:27.020
we actually did a PSA
competition in China.

00:39:27.020 --> 00:39:29.600
And like a million people voted
on the competition.

00:39:29.600 --> 00:39:31.610
But maybe we could do something
with YouTube about

00:39:31.610 --> 00:39:34.300
how would you get this message
over and use that.

00:39:34.300 --> 00:39:35.640
And can we make it go viral?

00:39:35.640 --> 00:39:38.450
And I think there's tremendous
usage there.

00:39:38.450 --> 00:39:41.640
And then similarly with some
of the technology on the

00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:42.650
marine protected areas.

00:39:42.650 --> 00:39:44.760
Again, I know Google's
funded some work

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:46.300
on drones, for example.

00:39:46.300 --> 00:39:48.760
There's definitely a good
connection there.

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:50.870
But I think from my point of
view, it's how can we use

00:39:50.870 --> 00:39:53.480
social media to get the message
out wider and more

00:39:53.480 --> 00:39:55.945
consistently and make some
of these things go viral?

00:39:55.945 --> 00:39:56.400
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:39:56.400 --> 00:39:56.945
Thank you.

00:39:56.945 --> 00:39:57.735
PETER KNIGHTS: Thank you.

