And it's also about just trying
to make these things

00:42:20.830 --> 00:42:21.800
fashionable, if you like.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:24.560
Because somebody said, what
are you trying to do?

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:27.080
It's like I'm trying to brand
conservation in China.

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:30.270
The conservation is just like a
Nike or something like that,

00:42:30.270 --> 00:42:31.590
that it's something that
people aspire to.

00:42:31.590 --> 00:42:32.340
They have a good feeling.

00:42:32.340 --> 00:42:34.060
It's not just about saying
don't buy it.

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:37.770
It's about saying I want to
be on Yao Ming's side.

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:40.410
I want to be part of his team,
and things like that.

00:42:40.410 --> 00:42:41.830
And I think that's
very important.

00:42:41.830 --> 00:42:43.610
And from what we've seen so far,
particularly the social

00:42:43.610 --> 00:42:46.910
media, there was an internet
survey done.

00:42:46.910 --> 00:42:49.460
27,500 people said ban
the shark fin and

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:51.740
400 people said don't.

00:42:51.740 --> 00:42:53.985
So particularly the young
communities, there's a strong,

00:42:53.985 --> 00:42:55.800
strong feeling for this stuff.

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:56.560
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:42:56.560 --> 00:43:00.630
You mentioned that there
is that, I guess, shark

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:04.610
fishermen's trade union or trade
organization that kind

00:43:04.610 --> 00:43:05.820
of sued you.

00:43:05.820 --> 00:43:09.190
In the United States, there's
a lot of media that kind of

00:43:09.190 --> 00:43:11.570
attacks people who try
to get the message

00:43:11.570 --> 00:43:13.100
out on climate change.

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:15.740
I was wondering do you see that
often in other types of

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:18.460
conservation, like maybe
traditional medicine, like

00:43:18.460 --> 00:43:20.550
some sort of trade organizations
or something?

00:43:20.550 --> 00:43:21.050
PETER KNIGHTS: Yeah.

00:43:21.050 --> 00:43:22.660
Traditional medicine isn't
very well organized.

00:43:22.660 --> 00:43:24.810
The shark fin traders
who tried to sue us.

00:43:24.810 --> 00:43:28.680
And again, they were pretty
stupid frankly, because

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:31.780
ultimately the whole campaign
just kept the campaign alive.

00:43:31.780 --> 00:43:35.040
It was in the news every
day in Thailand.

00:43:35.040 --> 00:43:36.930
And it became more of a
self-fulfilling prophecy than

00:43:36.930 --> 00:43:37.690
shutting us up.

00:43:37.690 --> 00:43:39.380
And in the end, the judge found
that everything we said

00:43:39.380 --> 00:43:40.310
was accurate.

00:43:40.310 --> 00:43:41.910
So it didn't really
do them very good.

00:43:41.910 --> 00:43:45.900
But US is obviously probably
the most litigious place on

00:43:45.900 --> 00:43:46.380
the planet.

00:43:46.380 --> 00:43:47.540
But yeah.

00:43:47.540 --> 00:43:48.750
And you see that here--

00:43:48.750 --> 00:43:51.230
I think the debate, the sort
of gag orders on food, on

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:52.720
commenting on food.

00:43:52.720 --> 00:43:54.170
We're the democratic country.

00:43:54.170 --> 00:43:58.180
And ironically, in China, the
shark fin traders, I was told,

00:43:58.180 --> 00:44:01.570
went to the government and said,
oh, these people are

00:44:01.570 --> 00:44:03.345
attacking our business, and you
should close them, and Yao

00:44:03.345 --> 00:44:04.220
Ming shouldn't be involved.

00:44:04.220 --> 00:44:06.140
And the government said,
actually, it's up to Yao Ming.

00:44:06.140 --> 00:44:09.280
If he wants to be involved,
that's fine.

00:44:09.280 --> 00:44:12.240
Also ironic that the images that
we have, the hard images,

00:44:12.240 --> 00:44:14.050
which you do have to show.

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:15.496
The amount of people that have
come up to me and said I don't

00:44:15.496 --> 00:44:17.480
eat shark fin soup any more
because I saw how they were

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:18.990
killing the sharks.

00:44:18.990 --> 00:44:20.540
It's very, very powerful
to show that.

00:44:20.540 --> 00:44:22.020
We wouldn't be able to
show that on US TV.

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:23.320
It would be censored or cut.

00:44:23.320 --> 00:44:25.290
Because if you've got blood or
anything with animals, they

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:27.700
don't-- they'll show you all
kinds of horrible things in

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:30.800
movies, but when it comes to
anything nasty happening to

00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:32.700
animals, there's big
restrictions on it.

00:44:32.700 --> 00:44:33.650
In China, they haven't.

00:44:33.650 --> 00:44:36.210
They've showed that footage even
at prime time and haven't

00:44:36.210 --> 00:44:39.992
really culled back, which,
again, is encouraging.

00:44:39.992 --> 00:44:44.890
DIANE SOLINGER: What about
labeling of products?

00:44:44.890 --> 00:44:47.020
Is that something that
you're seeing?

00:44:47.020 --> 00:44:50.680
Remember that the no animal
testing type of

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:51.530
stuff or you know?

00:44:51.530 --> 00:44:52.480
PETER KNIGHTS: It's starting.

00:44:52.480 --> 00:44:55.020
All the trends that happen over
here are starting to take

00:44:55.020 --> 00:44:56.050
on in China.

00:44:56.050 --> 00:44:58.250
And so, for example, one of the
things we're trying to do

00:44:58.250 --> 00:45:00.630
on climate change is they have
an energy labeling scheme with

00:45:00.630 --> 00:45:02.820
like rating for appliances.

00:45:02.820 --> 00:45:06.140
And there's one problem in that
when they did the scheme

00:45:06.140 --> 00:45:07.850
originally, they didn't
calibrate it properly.

00:45:07.850 --> 00:45:09.930
So we've got to try and work
with the government to get it

00:45:09.930 --> 00:45:11.020
recalibrated.

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:13.010
But then there's been
no promotion of it.

00:45:13.010 --> 00:45:15.430
So they've got compulsory energy
labelling, but nobody's

00:45:15.430 --> 00:45:16.890
gone out and said, this is
why you should use it.

00:45:16.890 --> 00:45:21.050
Or what I want to do is say
you'll save this much money by

00:45:21.050 --> 00:45:23.430
buying this unit, and
things like that.

00:45:23.430 --> 00:45:24.670
So yeah.

00:45:24.670 --> 00:45:27.530
All that stuff is-- everything
we do here is in China now.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:30.660
China is so changed since
I've been working there.

00:45:30.660 --> 00:45:33.910
So much of what's going on
in China is cutting edge.

00:45:33.910 --> 00:45:35.630
I was speaking to somebody
from James Cameron's

00:45:35.630 --> 00:45:36.510
organization yesterday.

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:39.800
They've got a big studio they're
building in China, 3D.

00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:42.760
And I think China is a pretty
sophisticated place in many

00:45:42.760 --> 00:45:45.350
ways now and in many different
places, and I think one of

00:45:45.350 --> 00:45:47.450
most capable countries in
the world, frankly.

00:45:47.450 --> 00:45:50.370
And I think if we can get them
on this, then I think they can

00:45:50.370 --> 00:45:53.930
solve this problem
pretty quickly.

00:45:53.930 --> 00:45:54.130
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:55.366
PETER KNIGHTS: Hi.

00:45:55.366 --> 00:45:57.600
AUDIENCE: So it sounds like
WildAid is very focused on

00:45:57.600 --> 00:46:00.290
conservation and on endangered
species.

00:46:00.290 --> 00:46:03.090
And I don't know much about it
yet, but I recently learned

00:46:03.090 --> 00:46:09.130
that China also has bear farms
and they use bear materials

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:10.290
for various medical uses.

00:46:10.290 --> 00:46:13.380
And I was wondering what's your
opinion on the need to

00:46:13.380 --> 00:46:15.950
publicize animals that aren't
necessarily endangered but

00:46:15.950 --> 00:46:17.360
maybe should be wild.

00:46:17.360 --> 00:46:19.080
They are mistreated.

00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:22.050
And people still aren't aware
of what happens to the

00:46:22.050 --> 00:46:23.720
products that they receive.

00:46:23.720 --> 00:46:25.710
PETER KNIGHTS: Yeah, the bears
is an interesting one.

00:46:25.710 --> 00:46:28.080
I actually filmed those bear
farms back in-- oh my god, I

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:28.970
don't want to date
myself here--

00:46:28.970 --> 00:46:30.420
1995.

00:46:30.420 --> 00:46:34.190
And the one thing about bear
gall is this is the one that

00:46:34.190 --> 00:46:35.010
really works.

00:46:35.010 --> 00:46:37.150
This is actually something
that has properties.

00:46:37.150 --> 00:46:40.200
And what we've done in Western
medicine is we've taken that

00:46:40.200 --> 00:46:43.180
property, which is a unique
acid which occurs in bear

00:46:43.180 --> 00:46:44.860
bile, and we synthesized it.

00:46:44.860 --> 00:46:46.870
And we can make them like
we can make aspirins.

00:46:46.870 --> 00:46:48.630
And that's the steps they
haven't made in China.

00:46:48.630 --> 00:46:50.745
They've gone halfway, which is
to mechanize the process,

00:46:50.745 --> 00:46:53.420
which is to put these bears
into these horrible farms

00:46:53.420 --> 00:46:55.640
where literally these
bears are in a cage

00:46:55.640 --> 00:46:56.930
the size of the bear.

00:46:56.930 --> 00:47:00.020
And daily, they will milk
the bile from them.

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:03.711
And we have done some
work on that.

00:47:03.711 --> 00:47:06.390
There's more sensitivity to
that, funnily enough, because

00:47:06.390 --> 00:47:09.590
it is seen as a part of
traditional medicine, and for

00:47:09.590 --> 00:47:11.925
a lot of people in China, the
only medicine system is

00:47:11.925 --> 00:47:12.870
traditional medicine.

00:47:12.870 --> 00:47:14.880
So the government is very,
very defensive

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:16.310
of traditional medicine.

00:47:16.310 --> 00:47:20.380
But what we've tried to do
with that is work with

00:47:20.380 --> 00:47:21.940
traditional medicine
practitioners who will say

00:47:21.940 --> 00:47:23.490
there's alternatives within
traditional medicine.

00:47:23.490 --> 00:47:25.260
There's other things
you can use

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:26.270
within traditional medicine.

00:47:26.270 --> 00:47:28.220
Because a lot of people use
traditional medicine because

00:47:28.220 --> 00:47:29.500
it's cheap.

00:47:29.500 --> 00:47:31.200
The irony with these endangered
species products,

00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:32.410
they're very expensive.

00:47:32.410 --> 00:47:34.240
So that is another campaign.

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:35.990
Again, it's part
desensitization.

00:47:35.990 --> 00:47:38.130
It's taken off in China now so
there's opposition within

00:47:38.130 --> 00:47:41.050
China itself to the whole
bear farming industry.

00:47:41.050 --> 00:47:43.690
But that's still one
that's out there.

00:47:43.690 --> 00:47:46.910
They also have tigers in tiger
farms, as well, nearly 10,000

00:47:46.910 --> 00:47:48.120
tigers in tiger farms.

00:47:48.120 --> 00:47:51.100
And there was a big move to
try and legalize tiger

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:52.850
products from these
tiger farms.

00:47:52.850 --> 00:47:55.390
And working with Jackie Chan and
Yao and people like that,

00:47:55.390 --> 00:47:58.410
we were able to head that
one off at the pass.

00:47:58.410 --> 00:48:00.480
Because the danger is with these
things is, particularly

00:48:00.480 --> 00:48:03.610
with traditional medicine, is
a belief that part of what

00:48:03.610 --> 00:48:05.640
you're doing is you're getting
the power of the animal.

00:48:05.640 --> 00:48:09.695
And so even though you might
have farm tigers, a farm tiger

00:48:09.695 --> 00:48:11.460
is not the same as
a wild tiger.

00:48:11.460 --> 00:48:13.670
So what you may be doing is all
you're doing is creating a

00:48:13.670 --> 00:48:14.340
mass market.

00:48:14.340 --> 00:48:15.970
There's still the market for
the high end stuff that's

00:48:15.970 --> 00:48:17.930
still there, which you
may be promoting.

00:48:17.930 --> 00:48:19.750
So we've done some
work on bears.

00:48:19.750 --> 00:48:22.750
I'd like to do some more work
one bears in the future.

00:48:22.750 --> 00:48:24.260
And the Asiatic bears
are endangered.

00:48:24.260 --> 00:48:28.072
There's only about
50,000 left.

00:48:28.072 --> 00:48:30.310
DIANE SOLINGER: You had another
question next to you?

00:48:30.310 --> 00:48:31.220
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:48:31.220 --> 00:48:35.080
I was just wondering, from all
of your experiences, what has

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:38.010
surprised you?

00:48:38.010 --> 00:48:38.640
PETER KNIGHTS: What
has surprised me?

00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:40.950
Good or bad?

00:48:40.950 --> 00:48:41.790
AUDIENCE: Whichever.

00:48:41.790 --> 00:48:45.570
PETER KNIGHTS: Well, I mean, I
think on the bad side, I think

00:48:45.570 --> 00:48:47.860
from doing the undercover
investigations, is just the

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:50.780
crazy things people will
do to animals.

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:53.490
It doesn't make sense,
a lot of the stuff.

00:48:53.490 --> 00:48:55.180
Because people in the bird
trade, for example--

00:48:55.180 --> 00:48:57.680
I did a lot of work on the wild
bird trade, which has

00:48:57.680 --> 00:48:59.850
been greatly decreased through
various efforts.

00:48:59.850 --> 00:49:02.960
But people were feeding baby
parrots, and they were using

00:49:02.960 --> 00:49:07.480
like ketchup bottles in like
a conveyor belt like this.

00:49:07.480 --> 00:49:08.740
And they would overfeed.

00:49:08.740 --> 00:49:12.600
It was being done so quickly and
roughly that three or four

00:49:12.600 --> 00:49:14.390
of these birds would choke
in the process.

00:49:14.390 --> 00:49:16.510
And you're like, that doesn't
make any sense.

00:49:16.510 --> 00:49:18.560
You're killing the things
you're trying to save.

00:49:18.560 --> 00:49:21.110
But when you have these
industrialized processes,

00:49:21.110 --> 00:49:21.980
people do crazy things.

00:49:21.980 --> 00:49:23.990
They put too many birds in the
box to try and save money,

00:49:23.990 --> 00:49:25.610
which ends up killing
them all.

00:49:25.610 --> 00:49:29.710
And so it surprised me how
irrationally people

00:49:29.710 --> 00:49:31.600
behave on that end.

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:35.260
I think on the other end what
surprised me is how quickly

00:49:35.260 --> 00:49:38.330
people in China and parts of
Asia have become sensitized to

00:49:38.330 --> 00:49:39.320
these issues.

00:49:39.320 --> 00:49:40.320
So people--

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:43.410
when we started this campaign,
people said, oh, you'll never

00:49:43.410 --> 00:49:44.030
change China.

00:49:44.030 --> 00:49:46.090
Oh, this has been thousands
of years.

00:49:46.090 --> 00:49:48.840
And my counter is, I don't think
there's been anywhere in

00:49:48.840 --> 00:49:50.790
the history of the planet that's
changed as quickly as

00:49:50.790 --> 00:49:53.470
China has changed in
the last 10 years.

00:49:53.470 --> 00:49:54.660
Everything has changed.

00:49:54.660 --> 00:49:55.940
It's a whole new ballgame.

00:49:55.940 --> 00:49:57.160
So we're not trying
to change things.

00:49:57.160 --> 00:49:58.950
We're trying to make this
part of the change.

00:49:58.950 --> 00:50:01.880
And what I've found and has
really heartened me and

00:50:01.880 --> 00:50:04.560
surprised me is how quickly
people get it, and when they

00:50:04.560 --> 00:50:07.680
get it, how they start
to switch to the

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:08.990
other side quite rapidly.

00:50:08.990 --> 00:50:10.440
An example is Taiwan.

00:50:10.440 --> 00:50:11.270
I did a lot of work there.

00:50:11.270 --> 00:50:14.220
And it wasn't that long ago when
people were involved in

00:50:14.220 --> 00:50:15.890
eating dogs, for example.

00:50:15.890 --> 00:50:18.330
And now people have a little
dog, and it's in the car, and

00:50:18.330 --> 00:50:19.100
it's driving there.

00:50:19.100 --> 00:50:22.270
And it's part of the family
and things like that.

00:50:22.270 --> 00:50:23.650
And that's happened
very quickly.

00:50:23.650 --> 00:50:26.340
Whereas in the West, our
sensitivity to animals has

00:50:26.340 --> 00:50:27.760
evolved over 300 years.

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:30.965
And if you were back in the
Industrial Revolution and you

00:50:30.965 --> 00:50:32.360
saw the way we treated
animals, you

00:50:32.360 --> 00:50:33.850
would be truly ashamed.

00:50:33.850 --> 00:50:35.520
And that's kind of where
China is now.

00:50:35.520 --> 00:50:37.810
But they have to make this
change in the space of 10

00:50:37.810 --> 00:50:38.465
years, not 300.

00:50:38.465 --> 00:50:39.500
And it's not just on this.

00:50:39.500 --> 00:50:40.340
It's on everything else.

00:50:40.340 --> 00:50:42.010
And what's amazing is
they are doing it.

00:50:42.010 --> 00:50:42.920
DIANE SOLINGER: They're
doing it, yeah.

00:50:42.920 --> 00:50:44.210
PETER KNIGHTS: And you
look at how smoking

00:50:44.210 --> 00:50:45.740
is reduced in China.

00:50:45.740 --> 00:50:47.240
It used to be everywhere.

00:50:47.240 --> 00:50:49.245
Now you go into Beijing,
and the taxis

00:50:49.245 --> 00:50:50.700
don't smell of smoke.

00:50:50.700 --> 00:50:52.410
Hotels don't smell of smoke.

00:50:52.410 --> 00:50:55.790
This has happened in like a
year, you've seen the changes.

00:50:55.790 --> 00:50:58.110
So the pace at which people
are capable of change has

00:50:58.110 --> 00:50:59.080
surprised me.

00:50:59.080 --> 00:51:00.820
And it also gives me
reason to hope.

00:51:00.820 --> 00:51:03.310
I believe we can do this in time
to save these species.

00:51:03.310 --> 00:51:03.740
DIANE SOLINGER: Thank you.

00:51:03.740 --> 00:51:08.970
In parting, right before you
leave, what do you think we

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:11.850
can do as Googlers, as
individuals, as YouTubers?

00:51:11.850 --> 00:51:12.870
What can we do?

00:51:12.870 --> 00:51:14.330
PETER KNIGHTS: Get involved
and spread the message of

00:51:14.330 --> 00:51:15.060
what's going on.

00:51:15.060 --> 00:51:18.990
And I think we'd love to work
with you guys more on how we

00:51:18.990 --> 00:51:22.270
can use social media to get
these messages out, get people

00:51:22.270 --> 00:51:24.810
involved and engaged, make
it cool, make it fun.

00:51:24.810 --> 00:51:28.480
Because again, the key to me on
any of these issues is very

00:51:28.480 --> 00:51:29.710
often we have a problem.

00:51:29.710 --> 00:51:30.960
It gets in the news.

00:51:30.960 --> 00:51:33.610
Its flavor of the month
for like a week, or 15

00:51:33.610 --> 00:51:34.800
seconds, as they say.

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:35.840
And then we move on.

00:51:35.840 --> 00:51:37.610
And the key to me about solving
these problems is

00:51:37.610 --> 00:51:39.720
keeping it out there for an
extended period, so people

00:51:39.720 --> 00:51:41.010
don't think it's solved
and go away.

00:51:41.010 --> 00:51:42.590
But they keep working.

00:51:42.590 --> 00:51:44.290
I think that's why we've had the
success with the sharks.

00:51:44.290 --> 00:51:45.950
And we've been working
it for a long time.

00:51:45.950 --> 00:51:46.795
And we haven't gone away.

00:51:46.795 --> 00:51:47.890
We haven't just done
a six-month

00:51:47.890 --> 00:51:48.600
campaign and given up.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:50.300
We just stayed on with
it and eventually--

00:51:50.300 --> 00:51:51.240
DIANE SOLINGER: It can't be the
next new shining thing.

00:51:51.240 --> 00:51:52.670
You got to stick with this
and stick with it.

00:51:52.670 --> 00:51:53.630
PETER KNIGHTS: And then
eventually you

